&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span&gt;Systemic Family Practitioner Trainee &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span&gt;Children and Young Peoples Improving Access to Psychological Therapies (CYP IAPT)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Hours: One-year fixed-term training post. Full Time only (due to University course commitments).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Location: Shropshire – Telford and Shrewsbury – University of Northampton &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;This is a one-year fixed term training post for Registered Mental Health Nurses Social Workers, Allied Health Professionals, and Psychological Therapists with post registration experience to work as a Trainee Systemic Family Practitioner in our exciting new partnership, the Bee u service. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;This post includes both working with in the Bee U service and committing to all aspects of the Post-Graduate Diploma course - Systemic Family Practice (SFP). The training is run in collaboration with the University of Northampton as part of Children and Young People Improving Access to Psychological Therapies (CYP-IAPT)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;The successful candidates will be working as Community Mental Health Practitioner within the Bee U service for the duration of the one year course and would split their time between training and carrying out direct clinical work in service. After the fixed term training contract ends applicants would be encouraged to apply for any vacant posts within the services or local partner agencies. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;The SFP course provides a thorough and robust theoretical base with particular focus on the protocols with the soundest evidence. In addition to providing practical, intensive and detailed skills training to facilitate skill development to a defined standard of competency, the course will aim to increase trainees’ knowledge base of theory and research in SFP and to promote a critical approach to the subject. It will aim to equip trainees to become skilled, creative and independent Systemic Family Practitioners who appropriately value and adhere to treatment protocols with fidelity. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;The training involves teaching blocks as well as weekly teaching and supervision days at the University of Northampton. Applicants must be willing to travel. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;The clinical work involves being part of a multi-disciplinary team and successful candidates will carry their own caseload of SFP training cases. Workplace supervision will be provided weekly in addition to supervisory support at University.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Please note in this instance the course is not optional; there will be a joint interview with the University of Northampton / CYP IAPT Midlands collaborative to appoint to this role. The role is dependent on meeting all course requirements. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;All applicants will need to be available to start the training in January 2021&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;For further information please contact&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Sherryn Ravenscroft&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Sherryn.ravenscroft@mpft.nhs.uk&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;0300 124 0093 &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
